master.notes: This first album by Midnight Sun is in fact the 2nd and re-recorded version of an album by Rainbow Band. After first recording their debut in 1970, Rainbow Band re-recorded the entire album in their new line-up with vocalist Allan Mortensen in 1971. After being forced to change their name, the same line-up re-released the album again using their new name.

master.notes: The 7" UK Rough Trade cat# RT 115 issue exists in different versions:• The original release from 1982, containing red labeled discs is as follows:1) [Riv] Riveters [url=https://img.discogs.com/P8RbscldD30xe4blZNYyK64D9FE=/fit-in/516x519/filters:strip_icc():format(jpeg):mode_rgb():quality(90)/discogs-images/R-410946-1273075767.jpeg.jpg](Men hammering rivets)[/url]"Robert Wyatt” - Red text."Shipbuilding / Memories Of You” - Green text. (Note slash, not center point)With a red paper label disc or a later red injection-print label disc.In 1983 there was a reissue with four different sleeves.• The 4 leporello sleeves each have a different cover image, taken from a [a2241169] series of shipyard paintings, credited accordingly on the back of each sleeve.Cover images (with 'Riggers' or "Riveters' credit on back) are:2) [Rg1] Riggers 1 [url=https://img.discogs.com/q8PPrPzPzUsWDZs1e0as22UHs4M=/fit-in/510x517/filters:strip_icc():format(jpeg):mode_rgb():quality(90)/discogs-images/R-1708247-1273072027.jpeg.jpg](Men with ropes)[/url]3)  [Rg2] Riggers 2 [url=https://img.discogs.com/OnkbvsXw4-XilyPyzd96jXyBipE=/fit-in/511x517/filters:strip_icc():format(jpeg):mode_rgb():quality(90)/discogs-images/R-1812521-1273072666.jpeg.jpg](Man and woman with tarpaulins)[/url]4)  [Rv1] Riveters 1 [url=https://img.discogs.com/JUenUCUMCX99EFJNIQU0N7rw4qE=/fit-in/511x517/filters:strip_icc():format(jpeg):mode_rgb():quality(90)/discogs-images/R-1812571-1273072443.jpeg.jpg](Men hammering rivets)[/url]5) [Rv2] Riveters 2 [url=https://img.discogs.com/mvxm8ZIRJKhK3LYSE0_xz-PZzcM=/fit-in/510x517/filters:strip_icc():format(jpeg):mode_rgb():quality(90)/discogs-images/R-1812538-1273072861.jpeg.jpg](Man at a brazier)[/url]• These 4 sleeves have a pale yellow text with colored drop shadow; "Robert Wyatt” - Red drop shadow."Shipbuilding • Memories Of You” - Green drop shadow.• Each 7" sleeve is printed on one side only, with 3 vertical folds, creating 4 pages-to-view [known in the print trade as a 'leporello']. It is 'roll-folded' around vinyl as follows; Cover opens to one side, revealing a facing page that opens to the other side. This reveals the vinyl in a white paper liner inserted into the 4th panel (which is tab-glued top & bottom to create [e.g] [url=https://img.discogs.com/DiOICeTmo5Wk34SK6XNuyhKm9mM=/fit-in/581x599/filters:strip_icc():format(jpeg):mode_rgb():quality(90)/discogs-images/R-1708247-1244982498.jpeg.jpg]a ⅓rd of page wallet[/url]).The disc liner has only one punch-hole, revealing the disc's green paper label.

master.notes: The original 1999 Japanese version was released nine months before the worldwide Ninja Tune edition and has a different tracklist: it includes two two tracks excised from the reissue versions ("Ritmo Tabaco" and "Picazón") and longer/alternate versions of some tracks ("Havana's Streets", "Kennedy's Secret Tapes", "Mamí"). "Havana's Streets" is longer and has a piano part throughout that is missing in later versions. "Kennedy's Secret Tapes" is longer and has many different elements as well. "Mami" is an alternate take, and longer. The mastering on the Japanese version is louder, brighter, and crisper than on the reissue versions.The 2000 reissue versions came out almost a year later and include two added tracks ("Back The Deal" and "Carbine 744, 520...Che Guevara"), as well as shorter, alternate versions of "Havana's Streets", "Kennedy's Secret Tapes", and "Mamí".

master.notes: Clifford Brown and Max Roach at Basin Street (aka At Basin Street) is a 1956 album by the Clifford Brown and Max Roach Quintet, the last album the quintet officially recorded. It is also one of the last major albums Brown recorded before his untimely death in 1956. The album was identified by Scott Yanow in his Allmusic essay "Hard Bop" as one of the 17 Essential Hard Bop Recordings.
